{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte ridicules the jurists' theory of a universal contract in *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, Chapter 4 (\"De l'occupation des choses\").**[^1]\n\nThe key passage reads: \"By what reasoning would one have succeeded in demonstrating to an inhabitant of Peru that he could not pick the fruit that grew at his hand, without infringing upon the rights of the inhabitants of Siberia? How would one have made an inhabitant of Kamchatka understand that he could not clothe himself in the skin of an animal, without injuring the rights of the Arabs? How would one have gone about showing the Gauls that they could not, in conscience, bring the plains of Auvergne under cultivation, without having obtained the permission of the inhabitants of Tibet?\"[^1]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, [p-5f2b15](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/04-de-loccupation-des-choses/translation/#p-5f2b15).",
